{"timestamp":"2026-07-19T16:48:17.840Z","type":"event_msg","payload":{"type":"token_count","info":{"total_token_usage":{"input_tokens":4474346604,"cached_input_tokens":4414070784,"cache_write_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":5628352,"reasoning_output_tokens":2045183,"total_tokens":4479974956},"last_token_usage":{"input_tokens":234565,"cached_input_tokens":233216,"cache_write_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":283,"reasoning_output_tokens":67,"total_tokens":234848},"model_context_window":258400},"rate_limits":{"limit_id":"codex","limit_name":null,"primary":null,"secondary":null,"credits":{"has_credits":true,"unlimited":true,"balance":null},"individual_limit":null,"spend_control_reached":null,"plan_type":"business","rate_limit_reached_type":null}}}
{"timestamp":"2026-07-19T16:48:55.824Z","type":"compacted","payload":{"first_window_id":"019f4ad9-7c3e-7723-95b1-7f5ac046b09e","message":"","previous_window_id":"019f7b26-857c-7b83-94ff-a3f8d00403b4","replacement_history":[{"content":[{"text":"Get us to latest origin main\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f5f47-7436-7a70-9426-77f7da1c0c05","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f4ad9-7d97-72d0-896c-a8c0ba674e35"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"I think we can get the .env from the main checkout for these missing variables\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f5f47-7436-7a70-9426-780d393a77a3","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"11ead30f-fa15-4fd5-9f2c-2ed2bbd7f22b"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Some less important sidequest, the neon container never seems to stop, maybe look into that as well on the side\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f5f47-7436-7a70-9426-781ced5332df","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"11ead30f-fa15-4fd5-9f2c-2ed2bbd7f22b"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"For the scanner, if it is likely, you can use playwright to simulate the camera. If that is too much work I would say it is okay to just open a scanner result URL and manually review the camera integration. It is probably too hard to fake the camera reliably.\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f5f47-7436-7a70-9426-7820e56db323","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"11ead30f-fa15-4fd5-9f2c-2ed2bbd7f22b"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Tell me what you are planning with rls?\nI don't think that is needed since our server handles authorization \n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f5f47-7436-7a70-9426-78355e540dff","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"02035f6f-50a5-476f-936a-ca8e95f3cfdc"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Update to the latest main state, I added some security updates in parallel\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f5f47-7436-7a70-9426-784425ebbab5","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"02035f6f-50a5-476f-936a-ca8e95f3cfdc"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Update to the latest main state, I added some security updates in parallel\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f5f47-7436-7a70-9426-7852423bf722","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"02035f6f-50a5-476f-936a-ca8e95f3cfdc"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Again we have a new security improvement on main, please align with the latest main on the way\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f5f47-7436-7a70-9426-78630111583d","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"02035f6f-50a5-476f-936a-ca8e95f3cfdc"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"What can we do to reduce the skipped tests to 0?\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f5f47-7436-7a70-9426-787fea85a9f1","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"e586b70d-cd25-4acd-ab98-636eb8eee8a2"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Add to our docs as a general guideline, tests HAVE TO pass ENTIRELY locally before a CI run is even attempted.\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f5f47-7436-7a70-9426-78896b6a66c9","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"e586b70d-cd25-4acd-ab98-636eb8eee8a2"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Small hint, please put these in the right places\n\nBinding product decisions:\nPaid event transactions are Stripe-only; without Stripe, events and add-ons must be free.\nA registration and all included, free, and purchased add-ons form one inseparable transfer bundle.\nAll quantities and fulfillment history transfer unchanged; the recipient cannot omit add-ons.\nTransfer pricing uses current base prices for the fixed bundle, then applies the recipient’s current eligible discounts. Source-user discounts do not transfer.\nThe source receives exact refunds for original Stripe payments; the recipient’s payment is independently recalculated.\nA transfer is database-only only when the entire bundle is free and no refund is required.\nExhausted emails remain stored/read-only; no recovery action is required for now.\nGoogle Maps is required production functionality. Cloudflare Images is being removed and is not a release gate.\nRemove the paid-cash cancellation documentation because it conflicts with the Stripe-only rule.\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f5f47-7436-7a70-9426-789b600d2287","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"a714695f-d340-488b-90bf-0fd649b61736"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Side-conversation handoff:\n\n- Ignore Fly-related work; a separate change is planned there.\n- Active ESNcard identifier: 2254268ZBWZ\n  Use it as E2E_LIVE_ESN_CARD_IDENTIFIER for local live-provider certification.\n- Permanently expired ESNcard identifier: 1995822SFGS\n  Use it for negative/expired-provider coverage if useful.\n- Keep both identifiers out of tracked files; use local .env or protected CI secrets.\n- The focused Google Maps rerun passed 8/8 with zero skips/flakes after the hydration wait. The full 11-test provider suite still needs a clean rerun.\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f5f47-7436-7a70-9426-78a674521110","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"3bd30c4a-63ca-41dc-ba2a-5538369d3f65"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"## Code review guidelines:\n# Review Guidelines\n\nYou are acting as a reviewer for a proposed code change made by another engineer.\n\nReview the change and respond in normal Markdown. Do not return JSON, XML, a findings object, or any structured review schema.\n\nWhen feedback should be attached directly to a changed line, emit one `::code-comment{...}` directive for that issue. The directive creates an inline code comment in the review UI; keep the visible response as normal Markdown. Emit no directives when there are no actionable inline comments.\n\nRequired `code-comment` attributes: `title`, `body`, and `file`. Optional attributes: `start`, `end`, and `priority`. Use the shortest useful line range. `file` should be an absolute path or include the workspace folder segment.\n\nFocus on discrete, actionable issues the original author would likely fix if they knew about them. Prefer no issues over speculative or low-signal feedback.\n\nGeneral guidelines for whether to call out an issue:\n\n1. It meaningfully impacts correctness, performance, security, or maintainability.\n2. It is discrete and actionable.\n3. It was introduced by the change under review.\n4. The author would likely fix it once aware.\n5. It does not rely on unstated assumptions about intent.\n6. It identifies the affected behavior clearly rather than speculating broadly.\n\nWhen you call out an issue, include the relevant file and line or function in prose, explain the scenario where it matters, and keep the explanation concise. Use priority labels such as `[P1]` or `[P2]` only when helpful to communicate severity.\n\nIf there are no actionable issues, say that directly and briefly.\nReview the code changes against the base branch 'origin/main'. The merge base commit for this comparison is ae92ec96bfa5683a2b3b78ea8c1a2ee48f47ea73. Run `git diff ae92ec96bfa5683a2b3b78ea8c1a2ee48f47ea73` to inspect the changes relative to origin/main. Provide concise, actionable feedback in a normal Markdown response.\n## My request for Codex:\nPlease review changes on codex/production-readiness-compliance against origin/main","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f5f47-7436-7a70-9426-78b375560b64","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f5a38-6448-76e3-ab2d-599d40299182"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Please fix these\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f5f47-7436-7a70-9426-78c36784f60d","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f5a6d-5f1b-7011-9703-f476c3e14e82"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"I think that the passwords are saved in the test files, please double check\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f5f47-7436-7a70-9426-78d41a97d965","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f5a84-015a-7b80-b859-dfe0accfdddf"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"## Code review guidelines:\n# Review Guidelines\n\nYou are acting as a reviewer for a proposed code change made by another engineer.\n\nReview the change and respond in normal Markdown. Do not return JSON, XML, a findings object, or any structured review schema.\n\nWhen feedback should be attached directly to a changed line, emit one `::code-comment{...}` directive for that issue. The directive creates an inline code comment in the review UI; keep the visible response as normal Markdown. Emit no directives when there are no actionable inline comments.\n\nRequired `code-comment` attributes: `title`, `body`, and `file`. Optional attributes: `start`, `end`, and `priority`. Use the shortest useful line range. `file` should be an absolute path or include the workspace folder segment.\n\nFocus on discrete, actionable issues the original author would likely fix if they knew about them. Prefer no issues over speculative or low-signal feedback.\n\nGeneral guidelines for whether to call out an issue:\n\n1. It meaningfully impacts correctness, performance, security, or maintainability.\n2. It is discrete and actionable.\n3. It was introduced by the change under review.\n4. The author would likely fix it once aware.\n5. It does not rely on unstated assumptions about intent.\n6. It identifies the affected behavior clearly rather than speculating broadly.\n\nWhen you call out an issue, include the relevant file and line or function in prose, explain the scenario where it matters, and keep the explanation concise. Use priority labels such as `[P1]` or `[P2]` only when helpful to communicate severity.\n\nIf there are no actionable issues, say that directly and briefly.\nReview the code changes against the base branch 'origin/main'. The merge base commit for this comparison is ae92ec96bfa5683a2b3b78ea8c1a2ee48f47ea73. Run `git diff ae92ec96bfa5683a2b3b78ea8c1a2ee48f47ea73` to inspect the changes relative to origin/main. Provide concise, actionable feedback in a normal Markdown response.\n## My request for Codex:\nPlease review changes on codex/production-readiness-compliance against origin/main","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f5f47-7436-7a70-9426-78e78b5e16da","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f5b20-93b4-7470-ad77-40085460211e"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Fix the issues\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f5f47-7436-7a70-9426-78f3e439f278","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f5b8c-1a1a-7402-bf3c-fc1a772faa61"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"## Code review guidelines:\n# Review Guidelines\n\nYou are acting as a reviewer for a proposed code change made by another engineer.\n\nReview the change and respond in normal Markdown. Do not return JSON, XML, a findings object, or any structured review schema.\n\nWhen feedback should be attached directly to a changed line, emit one `::code-comment{...}` directive for that issue. The directive creates an inline code comment in the review UI; keep the visible response as normal Markdown. Emit no directives when there are no actionable inline comments.\n\nRequired `code-comment` attributes: `title`, `body`, and `file`. Optional attributes: `start`, `end`, and `priority`. Use the shortest useful line range. `file` should be an absolute path or include the workspace folder segment.\n\nFocus on discrete, actionable issues the original author would likely fix if they knew about them. Prefer no issues over speculative or low-signal feedback.\n\nGeneral guidelines for whether to call out an issue:\n\n1. It meaningfully impacts correctness, performance, security, or maintainability.\n2. It is discrete and actionable.\n3. It was introduced by the change under review.\n4. The author would likely fix it once aware.\n5. It does not rely on unstated assumptions about intent.\n6. It identifies the affected behavior clearly rather than speculating broadly.\n\nWhen you call out an issue, include the relevant file and line or function in prose, explain the scenario where it matters, and keep the explanation concise. Use priority labels such as `[P1]` or `[P2]` only when helpful to communicate severity.\n\nIf there are no actionable issues, say that directly and briefly.\nReview the code changes against the base branch 'origin/main'. The merge base commit for this comparison is ae92ec96bfa5683a2b3b78ea8c1a2ee48f47ea73. Run `git diff ae92ec96bfa5683a2b3b78ea8c1a2ee48f47ea73` to inspect the changes relative to origin/main. Provide concise, actionable feedback in a normal Markdown response.\n## My request for Codex:\nPlease review changes on codex/production-readiness-compliance against origin/main","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f5f46-438d-7653-99e6-c97a99a016fb","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f5f46-2f32-7211-a155-6bd8e7889e2a"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Fix these issues\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f79a8-f54e-7cb1-b537-9ba77aa34d28","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f6179-2683-7c43-93af-ef14398c6222"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"I reset docker\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f79a8-f54e-7cb1-b537-9bb4237d1a48","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f64af-9210-7950-a2ad-591fc8f57290"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Please take me through the [APPLICATION_COMPLIANCE_AUDIT.md](APPLICATION_COMPLIANCE_AUDIT.md) \n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f79a8-f54e-7cb1-b537-9bcb620b253f","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f657c-0c5c-7a20-a85a-c2e386045dea"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Okay, we should get the local changes commited and the audit unified then\n\nLegacy migration will be planned only when we are functionally complete, then it is on a best effort basis.\n\nNext we will plan a migration for the new version to a differen hosting providerder and then manual browser testing in that new staging environment\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f79a8-f54e-7cb1-b537-9bd3a1909edf","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f6c8f-20ea-72b0-bdba-1a51e36455a8"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"\n# Files mentioned by the user:\n\n## PLAN (1).md: /Users/hedde/Downloads/PLAN (1).md\n\n## My request for Codex:\nGive this plan to move the hosting to scaleway a once over please and ask questions if things are unclear \n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f79a8-f54e-7cb1-b537-9be26e616808","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f6cb3-bb7d-7da3-ae19-7348fba86e4b"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"PLEASE IMPLEMENT THIS PLAN:\n# Scaleway Hosting Migration\n\n## Summary and locked decisions\n\n- Migrate staging first to Scaleway `fr-par`; keep production infrastructure defined but disabled and unprovisioned behind `PRODUCTION_ENABLED=false`.\n- Expose one tenant hostname per environment: `staging.evorto.app` initially and `alpha.evorto.app` for future production. Retain the current DNS provider and add only the required CNAME and email records. Scaleway supports this without an authoritative DNS transfer; document its 50-custom-domain container limit as a future scaling gate. [Custom domains](https://www.scaleway.com/en/docs/serverless-containers/how-to/add-a-custom-domain-to-a-container), [container limits](https://www.scaleway.com/en/docs/serverless-containers/reference-content/containers-limitations/)\n- Replace Neon Local with plain PostgreSQL 17 before the first staging deployment.\n- Remove Sentry immediately. Extend the existing Effect OpenTelemetry integration to Scaleway Cockpit.\n- Move Resend delivery to Scaleway Transactional Email using `Evorto \u003cno-reply@notifications.evorto.app\u003e`.\n- Introduce secure browser-to-Object-Storage receipt uploads now. Do not build rich-text media processing, public media hosting, Sharp, Edge Services, or a Cloudflare Images replacement.\n- Keep server-side authorization as the source of truth; add no RLS.\n- Leave Fly-related configuration untouched. Legacy data migration remains a separate, best-effort project after functional completion.\n\n## Application and runtime changes\n\n1. Split the single process using `APP_ROLE=web|worker|ops`, while building one immutable Linux/amd64 image:\n\n   - `web`: HTTP/RPC/SSR only; no background loops.\n   - `worker`: private authenticated container with bounded, idempotent endpoints for email delivery, expired-checkout cleanup, Stripe refund processing, and receipt-orphan cleanup. Configure separate CRON triggers with explicit paths and JSON arguments; Scaleway injects CRON arguments into the HTTP request body. [CRON triggers](https://www.scaleway.com/en/docs/serverless-containers/how-to/add-trigger-to-a-container/)\n   - `ops`: private authenticated container exposing only `schema-explain`, `schema-apply`, and `seed-staging`; no arbitrary command execution.\n   - Locally, run the worker in polling mode as a separate Compose service. Use CRON-triggered HTTP mode on Scaleway.\n   - Use private-network egress from all roles to PostgreSQL. Do not use Serverless Jobs because they currently lack VPC connectivity. [Container private networking](https://www.scaleway.com/en/docs/serverless-containers/reference-content/containers-private-networks/), [Jobs limitations](https://www.scaleway.com/en/docs/serverless-jobs/faq/)\n   - Package pinned Drizzle schema tooling into the final image and enforce an uncompressed image-size gate below 1 GB.\n\n2. Harden runtime interfaces:\n\n   - Retain DB-free `GET /healthz`.\n   - Harden `GET /readyz` to perform the existing behavioral SSR check using `READINESS_TENANT_HOST`, independent of Scaleway’s generated hostname.\n   - Add no-store `GET /version` returning `{ environment, revision, imageDigest }`.\n   - Resolve tenants from the real `Host` header, reject or ignore `X-Forwarded-Host`, and trust `X-Forwarded-Proto` only from the platform boundary.\n   - Add `POST /telemetry/browser-errors`: same-origin JSON only, 8 KiB maximum, redacted and truncated fields, instance-local deduplication/rate limiting, structured logging, and a `204` response.\n   - Add `APP_ENVIRONMENT`, `APP_REVISION`, `APP_IMAGE_DIGEST`, `READINESS_TENANT_HOST`, `WORKER_TRIGGER_MODE`, and bounded DB-pool settings. Remove Neon, Resend, and Sentry variables. Avoid application variables beginning with Scaleway’s reserved `SCW_` prefix.\n\n3. Refactor provider integrations:\n\n   - Replace R2-specific storage naming with an Effect `ObjectStorage` service backed by Scaleway S3, MinIO locally, and a fake in tests. Preserve server-mediated tenant-brand uploads.\n   - Use one private application-data bucket for tenant assets and receipts, with SSE-ONE, versioning, lifecycle rules, and exact-origin CORS. Maintain separate private buckets for Terraform state and deployment metadata. [SSE-ONE](https://www.scaleway.com/en/docs/object-storage/how-to/enable-sse-one/), [versioning](https://www.scaleway.com/en/docs/object-storage/how-to/use-bucket-versioning/), [lifecycle rules](https://www.scaleway.com/en/docs/object-storage/how-to/manage-lifecycle-rules/)\n   - Replace the base64 receipt RPC with:\n     - `createUpload({ eventId, fileName, mimeType, sizeBytes }) → { uploadId, url, fields, expiresAt }`\n     - `finalizeUpload({ uploadId }) → finalized upload`\n   - `createUpload` authorizes the user/tenant/event, creates a five-minute pending record, and signs an exact-key POST policy with type and size constraints. `finalizeUpload` reauthorizes, checks object size and magic bytes, permits only JPEG, PNG, WebP, and PDF, and becomes atomically idempotent. Receipt submission may consume only a ready upload bound to the same user, tenant, and event. Track `pending|ready|rejected|consumed`; clean expired orphans after a safety grace period. [Signed POST uploads](https://www.scaleway.com/en/docs/object-storage/api-cli/post-object)\n   - Introduce an Effect `EmailDelivery` service with TEM, Mailpit, and fake implementations. Preserve leases, attempts, backoff, and exhaustion history; rename provider-specific message fields to `provider` and `providerMessageId`.\n   - Add terminal `deliveryUnknown` for ambiguous post-dispatch failures and `suppressed` for staging recipients outside the protected allowlist. Never retry `deliveryUnknown`; keep exhausted and unknown emails read-only. Configure SPF, DKIM, MX, and DMARC-compatible records for `notifications.evorto.app`, preserving per-tenant Reply-To. [TEM setup](https://www.scaleway.com/en/docs/transactional-email/quickstart), [TEM API](https://www.scaleway.com/en/developers/api/transactional-email/emails)\n\n4. Replace local infrastructure:\n\n   - Use pinned PostgreSQL 17 with worktree-isolated ports and volumes; remove Neon API, proxy, expiration, and `NEON_*` plumbing.\n   - Retain MinIO and Stripe CLI, add Mailpit, and preserve `docker:start`, `docker:resume`, `docker:stop`, database, and E2E workflows.\n   - Keep destructive reset commands guarded to local hosts plus an explicit confirmation flag.\n\n## Scaleway infrastructure and delivery\n\n1. Terraform:\n\n   - Bootstrap a versioned private state bucket separately, then use the S3 backend with conditional lockfiles. [Scaleway Terraform backend](https://registry.terraform.io/providers/scaleway/scaleway/latest/docs/guides/backend_guide), [conditional writes](https://www.scaleway.com/en/docs/object-storage/api-cli/using-conditional-writes/)\n   - Define `evorto-staging` with VPC/private network, registry, PostgreSQL, IAM, Secret Manager, Cockpit, buckets, and the three container roles.\n   - Start staging PostgreSQL 17 as private-only `DB-DEV-S`, verified TLS, encryption at rest, separate least-privilege runtime/schema users, bounded connection pools, required extensions, daily backups retained seven days, and tested restoration.\n   - Define—but do not provision—`evorto-production` with HA `DB-POP2-2C-8G`, daily backups retained 30 days, a 24-hour RPO, and `alpha.evorto.app`. Measure restoration time during drills rather than promising an untested RTO. [Database responsibility and encryption](https://www.scaleway.com/en/docs/managed-databases-for-postgresql-and-mysql/reference-content/shared-responsibility-model/), [backups](https://www.scaleway.com/en/docs/managed-databases-for-postgresql-and-mysql/how-to/manage-backups/)\n   - Initially size containers at 560 mCPU/1 GB. Staging web uses min 0/max 3; worker and ops min 0/max 1. Future production web uses min 1/max 3.\n   - Keep static infrastructure in Terraform, but let deployment workflows own image revisions and secret environment values. Because Serverless Container secrets are not directly linked to Secret Manager, sync role-scoped secret values during deployment without placing them in Terraform state; mask logs and configure `ignore_changes` accordingly. [Container secret model](https://www.scaleway.com/en/docs/serverless-containers/concepts/)\n\n2. Observability and secrets:\n\n   - Extend existing Effect OTel with OTLP/HTTP trace export to Cockpit: 100% sampling in staging and 10% in production. Use native structured container logs with environment, role, revision, image digest, and request ID. [Cockpit traces](https://www.scaleway.com/en/docs/cockpit/how-to/activate-push-traces/), [container monitoring](https://www.scaleway.com/en/docs/serverless-containers/how-to/monitor-container/)\n   - Store private source maps outside the runtime image for 90 days, keyed by revision and digest.\n   - Configure alerts for 5xx/readiness failures, restarts, worker/ops failures, database saturation, storage/CPU, and billing.\n   - Scope secrets separately: web receives auth/session/Stripe webhook/runtime DB/storage; worker receives runtime DB/Stripe/TEM/storage; ops receives schema DB credentials. Rotate static IAM/API credentials on a documented schedule.\n\n3. CI and deployment:\n\n   - Normal PR/main CI runs format checking, lint, unit suites, PostgreSQL integration, build, Terraform validation/static scanning, release metadata checks, Linux/amd64 image build, SBOM, vulnerability scan, and image-size gate, ending in one required `CI/gate`.\n   - Keep protected credential/provider E2E separate from ordinary PR CI. PRs receive no Scaleway deployment credentials and use no `pull_request_target`.\n   - Deploy staging only after the exact `main` SHA passes both `CI/gate` and the protected baseline. Support automatic, manual, and 30-minute reconciliation triggers with deployment concurrency that never cancels an active deployment.\n   - Build once as `sha-\u003cfullsha\u003e`, resolve the digest, store source maps/SBOM and an append-only deployment manifest containing commit, digest, schema hash, workflow, and timestamp.\n   - Reconcile Terraform and secrets; deploy `ops` at the selected digest; run Drizzle explain and reject destructive schema plans; apply only backward-compatible schema changes. A staging reset requires a separate confirmed workflow.\n   - Deploy worker and web at the same digest, inject revision/digest metadata, and verify health, readiness, version, SSR/RPC, Auth0, Stripe test mode, TEM allowlisting, receipt uploads, tenant resolution, and `noindex`.\n   - On failure after traffic changes, redeploy the prior image digest. Database changes remain forward-only and backward compatible.\n   - Define a disabled production workflow that accepts only a successful staging manifest, copies the exact digest to the production registry without rebuilding, requires protected-environment approval, applies a safe schema plan, deploys, and smokes the release.\n\n## Verification and acceptance\n\n- Before any CI-triggering push, run the complete local equivalent with no filtering: format check, lint, all server/app unit suites, build, PostgreSQL integration, Playwright baseline/docs/integration projects, Terraform checks, Linux/amd64 image/security/size checks, the clean 11-test provider suite, and live ESNcard release certification.\n- Every collected test must pass: zero failures, skips, todos, fixmes, expected failures, retries/flakes, interruptions, or focused tests. Keep both ESNcard identifiers exclusively in local dotenv files or protected secrets.\n- Add focused tests for role isolation; worker idempotency and concurrency; Host spoofing; configured-host readiness; version metadata; telemetry redaction; TEM retry/unknown/suppressed states; TLS/pool/user separation; and signed-upload wrong-tenant, expiry, MIME spoofing, oversize, public-ACL, concurrent-finalize, and orphan scenarios.\n- After staging deployment, manually test anonymous/events, free and paid registration, add-ons, waitlists, cancellation, transfer, organizer operations, tenant/platform administration, receipts, Maps, and live providers in Browser. For the scanner, use a deterministic registration-result URL unless reliable camera emulation is straightforward; inspect console and network failures throughout.\n- Acceptance requires a successful restore drill, drift-reconciliation test, image rollback test, exact revision/digest proof, and confirmation that runtime artifacts contain no secrets, private source maps, Sentry, Neon, Resend, R2-specific, or Cloudflare Images dependencies.\n\n## Assumptions and deferred work\n\n- Staging is public but contains seeded/test data only and is marked `noindex`.\n- Existing Auth0, Stripe, Google Maps, Font Awesome, ESNcard, and Icons8 dependencies remain.\n- Paid event transactions remain Stripe-only; hosting work does not alter the established registration, add-on, refund, or transfer rules.\n- No RLS, Fly changes, legacy data migration, public media platform, or rich-text media pipeline is included.\n- Production resources and traffic remain disabled until staging browser testing, restore evidence, release certification, and a separate production-enablement decision are complete.\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f79a8-f54e-7cb1-b537-9bf2f73255ad","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f6cca-cf8a-73d3-ab8f-14c1ffb71c0e"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Take me through the deployment please\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f79a7-16a1-7332-a7a9-635de0bd89f4","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f79a6-ff99-7022-a86c-5ee2a273fd0d"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"I would like to remove all fly config and ideally the project as well\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f79aa-f634-7520-9b06-3fbac1f1b212","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f79a6-ff99-7022-a86c-5ee2a273fd0d"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"What is the issue now?\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f79b7-ac7e-70d3-b44f-dad7ae1bfadd","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f79a6-ff99-7022-a86c-5ee2a273fd0d"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"We can keep those since they are only in the dev tenant and not in any production system\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f79b8-4e6b-79a3-af68-dac44b4e1cd0","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f79a6-ff99-7022-a86c-5ee2a273fd0d"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"It is also okay if they are checked in\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f79b9-470c-74e0-bb78-7c7520191bd4","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f79a6-ff99-7022-a86c-5ee2a273fd0d"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Please do some reasearch about how to handle this issue with auth0 during testing, we can not seem to set port wildcards and also not plan every possible por\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f79bc-299f-7731-8435-a51c26292092","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f79a6-ff99-7022-a86c-5ee2a273fd0d"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"I think i will rather prepare a bunch of local ports that can be reused by worktrees, just use the default ones for this test\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f79f8-7fc8-7482-85ce-731f7a3d7d3b","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f79f8-7165-7b52-8e45-e80f97fd3a9b"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"I would also like to continue with our plan to deploy to scaleway, what is next\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f79f9-155b-7d91-8074-00b20fc4e686","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f79f9-07a1-75f2-ac1a-7cb4320f05dc"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Yes, use my mail.\nI can also add the scaleway info to the cli or terraform directly\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7a1e-2b56-79b1-90d4-f9290970b0f4","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7a1e-1c9d-7c50-be87-8aaccb2c1095"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"I added the scaleway config to the .env\nAnd I ran the suggested cli init command\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7a21-50df-70f3-a121-6ce809035a21","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7a1e-1c9d-7c50-be87-8aaccb2c1095"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Why do we have two databases?\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7a2d-91b6-72e0-828b-53cb3a1f5c9d","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7a2d-8414-7df1-8789-f22beb584eaa"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Alright, I have added the passwords\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7a2e-6cbc-7a22-9325-b9633d789b44","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7a2e-5d77-7262-8f14-56fa91a1926f"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Should I use a custom domain or use scaleway for now?\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7a3b-a384-7973-9c80-8f3bd44515f0","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7a2e-5d77-7262-8f14-56fa91a1926f"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"I added the plan, the domain is not configured\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7a3d-c163-7482-a9b5-096ea385294b","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7a2e-5d77-7262-8f14-56fa91a1926f"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Can we add the dns management via cloudflare to our terraform as well?\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7a42-047d-7632-8bc7-305823376d4f","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7a2e-5d77-7262-8f14-56fa91a1926f"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"\n# Files mentioned by the user:\n\n## evorto.app (1).txt: /Users/hedde/Downloads/evorto.app (1).txt\n\n## My request for Codex:\nI added the cloudflare values. Please make sure to keep the relevant settings  of what was there before\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7a49-ef7f-7b61-802e-ebc90ddebd56","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7a2e-5d77-7262-8f14-56fa91a1926f"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"We can remove the old alpha records, that is fine\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7a57-5edf-7af2-989c-0182cf98f72a","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7a57-4f67-7220-a35c-a3295ffaa816"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Explain again why we have three containers now?\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7a5a-672b-7411-9eac-7955f4f846f7","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7a5a-5961-7570-ba15-dc51e567d796"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Would we not do things like schema apply in github actions during deployment?\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7a5b-8505-7ce1-ba02-3ae65befaa80","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7a5b-762b-7bd3-85fd-35dc94c54229"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"How is the process working now\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7a5b-cf72-70a3-8a73-016027894c17","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7a5b-762b-7bd3-85fd-35dc94c54229"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"How does that work when we want to roll out a schema change and especially while we roll out incompatible schema changes during development?\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7a5f-19bb-7f50-8ec2-537523defc07","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7a5f-0c1c-7890-966b-3b1b7a079db0"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"when I try to open the application bucket in the scaleway console, I get an error message, I assume that is related to the policy, can we make that available in the console?\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7a61-3ea0-7c11-bb9c-897fd00c2a59","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7a61-3063-72b3-bc14-8651c86a6666"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"It seems like nothing works at the moment, I don't get any response on the domain or info in grafana, what are our next steps?\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7a73-884c-7243-9b33-c1e8d5b8a7d0","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7a73-79fd-70a3-9aa1-87cf2ae48e2e"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Help me take all needed steps\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7a7f-5db5-7950-944b-81145610116c","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7a7f-4ef0-7691-9ddd-368463dcf34f"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Once everything we have to prepare before merge is done, tell me to work on the merge\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7a9a-5d9f-7a41-ba38-bfb518b2dd5a","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7a7f-4ef0-7691-9ddd-368463dcf34f"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"We have to also make sure we are ready for the post merge deployment\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7a9f-29e7-7f12-a0cd-c717834077fb","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7a7f-4ef0-7691-9ddd-368463dcf34f"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Do we have uncommitted changes?\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7ada-5b92-7ff0-8fb3-82d0c5c411b6","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7ada-4da3-7d20-af10-658607fa8232"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"## Code review guidelines:\n# Review Guidelines\n\nYou are acting as a reviewer for a proposed code change made by another engineer.\n\nReview the change and respond in normal Markdown. Do not return JSON, XML, a findings object, or any structured review schema.\n\nWhen feedback should be attached directly to a changed line, emit one `::code-comment{...}` directive for that issue. The directive creates an inline code comment in the review UI; keep the visible response as normal Markdown. Emit no directives when there are no actionable inline comments.\n\nRequired `code-comment` attributes: `title`, `body`, and `file`. Optional attributes: `start`, `end`, and `priority`. Use the shortest useful line range. `file` should be an absolute path or include the workspace folder segment.\n\nFocus on discrete, actionable issues the original author would likely fix if they knew about them. Prefer no issues over speculative or low-signal feedback.\n\nGeneral guidelines for whether to call out an issue:\n\n1. It meaningfully impacts correctness, performance, security, or maintainability.\n2. It is discrete and actionable.\n3. It was introduced by the change under review.\n4. The author would likely fix it once aware.\n5. It does not rely on unstated assumptions about intent.\n6. It identifies the affected behavior clearly rather than speculating broadly.\n\nWhen you call out an issue, include the relevant file and line or function in prose, explain the scenario where it matters, and keep the explanation concise. Use priority labels such as `[P1]` or `[P2]` only when helpful to communicate severity.\n\nIf there are no actionable issues, say that directly and briefly.\nReview the code changes against the base branch 'origin/main'. The merge base commit for this comparison is ae92ec96bfa5683a2b3b78ea8c1a2ee48f47ea73. Run `git diff ae92ec96bfa5683a2b3b78ea8c1a2ee48f47ea73` to inspect the changes relative to origin/main. Provide concise, actionable feedback in a normal Markdown response.\n## My request for Codex:\nPlease review changes on codex/production-readiness-compliance against origin/main","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7adc-afbc-7523-a221-7b4063011d8b","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7adc-a098-7241-86b4-2a21387489c5"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Take care of the items and update the PR\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7ae6-0297-7673-a6c8-41b54ea8b08e","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7ae5-f39e-7fd3-9fe8-d4404e4e9860"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"## Code review guidelines:\n# Review Guidelines\n\nYou are acting as a reviewer for a proposed code change made by another engineer.\n\nReview the change and respond in normal Markdown. Do not return JSON, XML, a findings object, or any structured review schema.\n\nWhen feedback should be attached directly to a changed line, emit one `::code-comment{...}` directive for that issue. The directive creates an inline code comment in the review UI; keep the visible response as normal Markdown. Emit no directives when there are no actionable inline comments.\n\nRequired `code-comment` attributes: `title`, `body`, and `file`. Optional attributes: `start`, `end`, and `priority`. Use the shortest useful line range. `file` should be an absolute path or include the workspace folder segment.\n\nFocus on discrete, actionable issues the original author would likely fix if they knew about them. Prefer no issues over speculative or low-signal feedback.\n\nGeneral guidelines for whether to call out an issue:\n\n1. It meaningfully impacts correctness, performance, security, or maintainability.\n2. It is discrete and actionable.\n3. It was introduced by the change under review.\n4. The author would likely fix it once aware.\n5. It does not rely on unstated assumptions about intent.\n6. It identifies the affected behavior clearly rather than speculating broadly.\n\nWhen you call out an issue, include the relevant file and line or function in prose, explain the scenario where it matters, and keep the explanation concise. Use priority labels such as `[P1]` or `[P2]` only when helpful to communicate severity.\n\nIf there are no actionable issues, say that directly and briefly.\nReview the code changes against the base branch 'origin/main'. The merge base commit for this comparison is ae92ec96bfa5683a2b3b78ea8c1a2ee48f47ea73. Run `git diff ae92ec96bfa5683a2b3b78ea8c1a2ee48f47ea73` to inspect the changes relative to origin/main. Provide concise, actionable feedback in a normal Markdown response.\n## My request for Codex:\nPlease review changes on codex/production-readiness-compliance against origin/main","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7ae6-48ac-7413-b76d-6c9604753717","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7ae5-f39e-7fd3-9fe8-d4404e4e9860"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"Take care of the items and update the PR\n","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7ae6-9d72-7b80-bce6-4bcc11110d37","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7ae5-f39e-7fd3-9fe8-d4404e4e9860"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"## Code review guidelines:\n# Review Guidelines\n\nYou are acting as a reviewer for a proposed code change made by another engineer.\n\nReview the change and respond in normal Markdown. Do not return JSON, XML, a findings object, or any structured review schema.\n\nWhen feedback should be attached directly to a changed line, emit one `::code-comment{...}` directive for that issue. The directive creates an inline code comment in the review UI; keep the visible response as normal Markdown. Emit no directives when there are no actionable inline comments.\n\nRequired `code-comment` attributes: `title`, `body`, and `file`. Optional attributes: `start`, `end`, and `priority`. Use the shortest useful line range. `file` should be an absolute path or include the workspace folder segment.\n\nFocus on discrete, actionable issues the original author would likely fix if they knew about them. Prefer no issues over speculative or low-signal feedback.\n\nGeneral guidelines for whether to call out an issue:\n\n1. It meaningfully impacts correctness, performance, security, or maintainability.\n2. It is discrete and actionable.\n3. It was introduced by the change under review.\n4. The author would likely fix it once aware.\n5. It does not rely on unstated assumptions about intent.\n6. It identifies the affected behavior clearly rather than speculating broadly.\n\nWhen you call out an issue, include the relevant file and line or function in prose, explain the scenario where it matters, and keep the explanation concise. Use priority labels such as `[P1]` or `[P2]` only when helpful to communicate severity.\n\nIf there are no actionable issues, say that directly and briefly.\nReview the code changes against the base branch 'origin/main'. The merge base commit for this comparison is ae92ec96bfa5683a2b3b78ea8c1a2ee48f47ea73. Run `git diff ae92ec96bfa5683a2b3b78ea8c1a2ee48f47ea73` to inspect the changes relative to origin/main. Provide concise, actionable feedback in a normal Markdown response.\n## My request for Codex:\nPlease review changes on codex/production-readiness-compliance against origin/main","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7b09-fbfe-7391-9db8-0a48cae804c9","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7b09-e676-73d0-b108-1ca794ca9fa6"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"## Code review guidelines:\n# Review Guidelines\n\nYou are acting as a reviewer for a proposed code change made by another engineer.\n\nReview the change and respond in normal Markdown. Do not return JSON, XML, a findings object, or any structured review schema.\n\nWhen feedback should be attached directly to a changed line, emit one `::code-comment{...}` directive for that issue. The directive creates an inline code comment in the review UI; keep the visible response as normal Markdown. Emit no directives when there are no actionable inline comments.\n\nRequired `code-comment` attributes: `title`, `body`, and `file`. Optional attributes: `start`, `end`, and `priority`. Use the shortest useful line range. `file` should be an absolute path or include the workspace folder segment.\n\nFocus on discrete, actionable issues the original author would likely fix if they knew about them. Prefer no issues over speculative or low-signal feedback.\n\nGeneral guidelines for whether to call out an issue:\n\n1. It meaningfully impacts correctness, performance, security, or maintainability.\n2. It is discrete and actionable.\n3. It was introduced by the change under review.\n4. The author would likely fix it once aware.\n5. It does not rely on unstated assumptions about intent.\n6. It identifies the affected behavior clearly rather than speculating broadly.\n\nWhen you call out an issue, include the relevant file and line or function in prose, explain the scenario where it matters, and keep the explanation concise. Use priority labels such as `[P1]` or `[P2]` only when helpful to communicate severity.\n\nIf there are no actionable issues, say that directly and briefly.\nReview the code changes against the base branch 'origin/main'. The merge base commit for this comparison is ae92ec96bfa5683a2b3b78ea8c1a2ee48f47ea73. Run `git diff ae92ec96bfa5683a2b3b78ea8c1a2ee48f47ea73` to inspect the changes relative to origin/main. Provide concise, actionable feedback in a normal Markdown response.\n## My request for Codex:\nPlease review changes on codex/production-readiness-compliance against origin/main","type":"input_text"}],"id":"msg_019f7b38-5466-70b1-aa67-55048ca26fa6","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7b38-4500-7813-b5d3-41783cb5ae77"},"role":"user","type":"message"},{"content":[{"text":"\u003cpermissions instructions\u003e\nFilesystem sandboxing defines which files can be read or written. `sandbox_mode` is `danger-full-access`: No filesystem sandboxing - all commands are permitted. Network access is enabled.\nApproval policy is currently never. Do not provide the `sandbox_permissions` for any reason, commands will be rejected.\n\u003c/permissions instructions\u003e","type":"input_text"},{"text":"\u003capp-context\u003e\n# Codex desktop context\n- You are running inside the Codex (desktop) app, which allows some additional features not available in the CLI alone:\n\n### Images/Visuals/Files\n- In the app, the model can display images and videos using standard Markdown image syntax: ![alt](url)\n- When sending or referencing a local image or video, always use an absolute filesystem path in the Markdown image tag (e.g., ![alt](/absolute/path.png)); relative paths and plain text will not render the media.\n- When referencing code or workspace files in responses, always use full absolute file paths instead of relative paths.\n- If a user asks about an image, or asks you to create an image, it is often a good idea to show the image to them in your response.\n- Use mermaid diagrams to represent complex diagrams, graphs, or workflows. Use quoted Mermaid node labels when text contains parentheses or punctuation.\n- Return web URLs as Markdown links (e.g., [label](https://example.com)).\n\n### Workspace Dependencies\n- For sheets, slides, and documents, call `load_workspace_dependencies` to find the bundled runtime and libraries.\n\n### Automations\n- This app supports recurring automations, reminders, monitors, follow-ups, and thread wakeups. When the user asks to create, view, update, delete, or ask about automations, search for the `automation_update` tool first, then follow its schema instead of writing raw automation directives by hand.\n- When an automation should archive a Codex thread on completion, use `set_thread_archived` instead of emitting raw archive directives.\n\n### Thread Coordination\n- Treat the terms \"task\", \"thread\", \"chat\", and \"conversation\" as synonyms when they clearly refer to Codex. Tool names use the term \"thread\" and Codex uses \"task\" in the UI. When providing user-facing responses, use \"task\".\n- When the user asks to create, fork, inspect, continue, hand off, pin, archive, rename, or otherwise manage Codex threads, search for the relevant thread tool first: `create_thread`, `fork_thread`, `list_threads`, `read_thread`, `wait_threads`, `send_message_to_thread`, `handoff_thread`, `set_thread_pinned`, `set_thread_archived`, or `set_thread_title`.\n- When following another task's progress, prefer compact `wait_threads` snapshots over repeated `read_thread` calls. Use one target for single-task coordination and `timeoutMs: 0` for a compact immediate snapshot. `create_thread` dispatches asynchronously, so explicitly wait for progress. Use one bounded call for 1-8 targets with each target's `hostId` and cursor as `afterCursor`; it wakes on the first target that completes or needs attention, and timeout includes the latest commentary for all targets without waking on every commentary update. An up-to-date cursor suppresses already-delivered final text. Separate waits from one task may run serially. Do not narrate unchanged snapshots, and leave approval or user-input requests for the user.\n- Only use `create_thread` when the user explicitly asks to create a new thread. Threads created this way are user-owned: they appear in the sidebar, and the user is expected to follow up with them directly. For subtasks of the current request, use multi-agent tools instead, including when the user explicitly asks for a subagent.\n- After a successful `create_thread` call, emit `::created-thread{threadId=\"...\"}` for a created thread or `::created-thread{clientThreadId=\"...\"}` for queued worktree setup on its own line in your final response.\n\n### Inline Code Comments\n- Use the ::code-comment{...} directive when you need to attach feedback directly to specific code lines.\n- Emit one directive per inline comment; emit none when there are no actionable inline comments.\n- Required attributes: title (short label), body (one-paragraph explanation), file (path to the file).\n- Optional attributes: start, end (1-based line numbers), priority (0-3).\n- file should be an absolute path or include the workspace folder segment so it can be resolved relative to the workspace.\n- Keep line ranges tight; end defaults to start.\n- Example: ::code-comment{title=\"[P2] Off-by-one\" body=\"Loop iterates past the end when length is 0.\" file=\"/path/to/foo.ts\" start=10 end=11 priority=2}\n\n### Git\n- Branch prefix: `codex/`. Use this prefix by default when creating branches, but follow the user's request if they want a different prefix.\n- Pull request instructions: Pull request titles should follow conventional commit style.\n- After successfully staging files, emit `::git-stage{cwd=\"/absolute/path\"}` on its own line in your final response.\n- After successfully creating a commit, emit `::git-commit{cwd=\"/absolute/path\"}` on its own line in your final response.\n- After successfully creating or switching the thread onto a branch, emit `::git-create-branch{cwd=\"/absolute/path\" branch=\"branch-name\"}` on its own line in your final response.\n- After successfully pushing the current branch, emit `::git-push{cwd=\"/absolute/path\" branch=\"branch-name\"}` on its own line in your final response.\n- After successfully creating a pull request, emit `::git-create-pr{cwd=\"/absolute/path\" branch=\"branch-name\" url=\"https://...\" isDraft=true}` on its own line in your final response. Include `isDraft=false` for ready PRs.\n- Only emit these git directives in your final response after the action actually succeeds, never in commentary updates. Keep attributes single-line.\n\u003c/app-context\u003e","type":"input_text"},{"text":"\u003ccollaboration_mode\u003e# Collaboration Mode: Default\n\nYou are now in Default mode. Any previous instructions for other modes (e.g. Plan mode) are no longer active.\n\nYour active mode changes only when new developer instructions with a different `\u003ccollaboration_mode\u003e...\u003c/collaboration_mode\u003e` change it; user requests or tool descriptions do not change mode by themselves. Known mode names are Default and Plan.\n\n## request_user_input availability\n\nUse the `request_user_input` tool only when it is listed in the available tools for this turn.\n\nIn Default mode, strongly prefer making reasonable assumptions and executing the user's request rather than stopping to ask questions. If you absolutely must ask a question because the answer cannot be discovered from local context and a reasonable assumption would be risky, ask the user directly with a concise plain-text question. Never write a multiple choice question as a textual assistant message.\n\u003c/collaboration_mode\u003e","type":"input_text"},{"text":"## Memory\n\nYou have access to a memory folder with guidance from prior runs. It can save\ntime and help you stay consistent. Use it whenever it is likely to help.\n\nDecision boundary: should you use memory for a new user query?\n\n- Skip memory ONLY when the request is clearly self-contained and does not need\n  workspace history, conventions, or prior decisions.\n- Hard skip examples: current time/date, simple translation, simple sentence\n  rewrite, one-line shell command, trivial formatting.\n- Use memory by default when ANY of these are true:\n  - the query mentions workspace/repo/module/path/files in MEMORY_SUMMARY below,\n  - the user asks for prior context / consistency / previous decisions,\n  - the task is ambiguous and could depend on earlier project choices,\n  - the ask is a non-trivial and related to MEMORY_SUMMARY below.\n- If unsure, do a quick memory pass.\n\nMemory layout (general -\u003e specific):\n\n- /Users/hedde/.codex/memories/memory_summary.md (already provided below; do NOT open again)\n- /Users/hedde/.codex/memories/MEMORY.md (searchable registry; primary file to query)\n- /Users/hedde/.codex/memories/skills/\u003cskill-name\u003e/ (skill folder)\n  - SKILL.md (entrypoint instructions)\n  - scripts/ (optional helper scripts)\n  - examples/ (optional example outputs)\n  - templates/ (optional templates)\n- /Users/hedde/.codex/memories/rollout_summaries/ (per-rollout recaps + evidence snippets)\n  - The paths of these entries can be found in /Users/hedde/.codex/memories/MEMORY.md or /Users/hedde/.codex/memories/rollout_summaries/ as `rollout_path`\n  - These files are append-only `jsonl`: `session_meta.payload.id` identifies the session, `turn_context` marks turn boundaries, `event_msg` is the lightweight status stream, and `response_item` contains actual messages, tool calls, and tool outputs.\n  - For efficient lookup, prefer matching the filename suffix or `session_meta.payload.id`; avoid broad full-content scans unless needed.\n\nQuick memory pass (when applicable):\n\n1. Skim the MEMORY_SUMMARY below and extract task-relevant keywords.\n2. Search /Users/hedde/.codex/memories/MEMORY.md using those keywords.\n3. Only if MEMORY.md directly points to rollout summaries/skills, open the 1-2\n   most relevant files under /Users/hedde/.codex/memories/rollout_summaries/ or\n   /Users/hedde/.codex/memories/skills/.\n4. If above are not clear and you need exact commands, error text, or precise evidence, search over `rollout_path` for more evidence.\n5. If there are no relevant hits, stop memory lookup and continue normally.\n\nQuick-pass budget:\n\n- Keep memory lookup lightweight: ideally \u003c= 4-6 search steps before main work.\n- Avoid broad scans of all rollout summaries.\n\nDuring execution: if you hit repeated errors, confusing behavior, or suspect\nrelevant prior context, redo the quick memory pass.\n\nHow to decide whether to verify memory:\n\n- Consider both risk of drift and verification effort.\n- If a fact is likely to drift and is cheap to verify, verify it before\n  answering.\n- If a fact is likely to drift but verification is expensive, slow, or\n  disruptive, it is acceptable to answer from memory in an interactive turn,\n  but you should say that it is memory-derived, note that it may be stale, and\n  consider offering to refresh it live.\n- If a fact is lower-drift and expensive to verify, it is usually fine to\n  answer from memory directly.\n\nWhen answering from memory without current verification:\n\n- If you rely on memory for a fact that you did not verify in the current turn,\n  say so briefly in the final answer.\n- If that fact is plausibly drift-prone or comes from an older note, older\n  snapshot, or prior run summary, say that it may be stale or outdated.\n- If live verification was skipped and a refresh would be useful in the\n  interactive context, consider offering to verify or refresh it live.\n- Do not present unverified memory-derived facts as confirmed-current.\n- Prefer a short refresh offer for interactive questions, especially about prior\n  results, commands, timing, or older snapshots.\n\nMemory citation requirements:\n\n- If ANY relevant memory files were used: append exactly one\n`\u003coai-mem-citation\u003e` block as the VERY LAST content of the final reply.\n  Normal responses should include the answer first, then append the\n`\u003coai-mem-citation\u003e` block at the end.\n- Use this exact structure for programmatic parsing:\n```\n\u003coai-mem-citation\u003e\n\u003ccitation_entries\u003e\nMEMORY.md:234-236|note=[responsesapi citation extraction code pointer]\nrollout_summaries/2026-02-17T21-23-02-LN3m-example.md:10-12|note=[weekly report format]\n\u003c/citation_entries\u003e\n\u003crollout_ids\u003e\n019c6e27-e55b-73d1-87d8-4e01f1f75043\n019c7714-3b77-74d1-9866-e1f484aae2ab\n\u003c/rollout_ids\u003e\n\u003c/oai-mem-citation\u003e\n```\n- `citation_entries` is for rendering:\n  - one citation entry per line\n  - format: `\u003cfile\u003e:\u003cline_start\u003e-\u003cline_end\u003e|note=[\u003chow memory was used\u003e]`\n  - use file paths relative to the memory base path (for example, `MEMORY.md`,\n    `rollout_summaries/...`, `skills/...`)\n  - only cite files actually used under the memory base path (do not cite\n    workspace files as memory citations)\n  - if you used `MEMORY.md` and then a rollout summary/skill file, cite both\n  - list entries in order of importance (most important first)\n  - `note` should be short, single-line, and use simple characters only (avoid\n    unusual symbols, no newlines)\n- `rollout_ids` is for us to track what previous rollouts you find useful:\n  - include one rollout id per line\n  - rollout ids should look like UUIDs (for example,\n    `019c6e27-e55b-73d1-87d8-4e01f1f75043`)\n  - include unique ids only; do not repeat ids\n  - an empty `\u003crollout_ids\u003e` section is allowed if no rollout ids are available\n  - you can find rollout ids in rollout summary files and MEMORY.md\n  - do not include file paths or notes in this section\n  - For every `citation_entries`, try to find and cite the corresponding rollout id if possible\n- Never include memory citations inside pull-request messages.\n- Never cite blank lines; double-check ranges.\n\nUpdating memories:\n\nYou can update the memories **only** when explicitly asked by the user. This must always come from a direct request from the user.\n- Write your update in /Users/hedde/.codex/memories/extensions/ad_hoc/notes/\n- Each update must be one small file containing what you want to add/delete/update from the memories.\n- The name of this file must be `\u003ctimestamp\u003e-\u003cshort slug\u003e.md`\n- Do not try to edit the memory files yourself, only add one update note in /Users/hedde/.codex/memories/extensions/ad_hoc/notes/\n\n========= MEMORY_SUMMARY BEGINS =========\nv1\n\n## User Profile\n\nThe user works repeatedly across `section-app`, `evorto-app/app`, `evorto-pages`, `Window watcher`, `/Users/hedde/code/effect-angular`, `/Users/hedde/code/docs-tests`, `/Users/hedde/code/evorto`, and an Artifacts MMO prototype. They use memory as an execution aid: they want exact retrieval handles, durable artifacts, and behavior-changing preferences preserved. They repeatedly prefer evidence-backed execution over guesses, especially for deployment, infrastructure, security, and “how does this work right now” questions. They often want the latest remote `main`/`master` synced before audits, scans, or release/deploy work. For user-facing behavior, they prefer explicit blocked-action/state explanations instead of silent failures or vague messaging. In relaunch-stack Evorto work, they want direct work against the new schema rather than migration layers. [ad-hoc note]\n\n## User preferences\n\n- When they ask to get to the latest `main` or `master` and then audit/scan/update, sync to the remote first instead of working from stale local state.\n- When they ask for a broad audit or review, start with repo inventory/docs and leave a durable artifact with findings or open questions instead of a chat-only recap.\n- When Browser verification is requested for UI work, keep it distinct from Playwright/static evidence; if Browser control is unavailable, report manual acceptance as blocked rather than claiming a substitute passed.\n- When requirements or product decisions are missing, ask/record the open questions rather than silently narrowing a complete-production objective.\n- When they ask how something works “at the moment”, trace the current UI -\u003e RPC -\u003e server path rather than describing intended behavior.\n- When they ask to debug or verify locally, default to Browser-assisted reproduction and real local verification before pushing.\n- For confirmed API compatibility work, use the live official contract first and preserve explicitly accepted prototype scope instead of adding general production hardening.\n- When a model/planner failure may be timeout or context-related, trace timing, prompt size, and runtime logs first; prefer removing redundant model work in favor of local deterministic validation over raising timeouts.\n- For `section-app`, treat “DO NOT connect to the prod db” / “UNDER NO CIRCUMSTANCE connect to the main prod db” as a hard rule; prefer DB-free, local-only, Docker-avoiding verification.\n- When they say not to interfere with another local project or Docker usage, check ports/process isolation first and avoid broad local runtime changes.\n- When they flag overlap with another PR, pause and coordinate before extending the same area; wait, sync to `main`, and trim duplicates after the other PR lands.\n- When they ask to push, open a PR, merge, or “make sure it deploys”, carry the workflow through commit/push/deploy verification instead of stopping at code changes.\n- When they ask for a broad repo review and it surfaces a real bug, implement the fix and prove it locally and in production instead of stopping at an advisory.\n- When a browser/settings auth flow is broken, give concise terminal commands the user can run themselves instead of trying to keep them inside the broken tab.\n- In `evorto-app/app` relaunch work, do not add or maintain migration code; work against the new schema directly and treat old-to-new transfer as a separate TypeScript job. [ad-hoc note]\n- For blocked actions, registration/payment states, permissions, and similar edge cases, lean toward explaining a little too much rather than leaving users guessing. [ad-hoc note]\n\n## General Tips\n\n- In `evorto-app/app`, start current audits with `PRODUCT.md`, `ARCHITECTURE.md`, `QUALITY.md`, and `APPLICATION_COMPLIANCE_AUDIT.md`; `STABILIZATION.md` was removed on a newer latest-main checkout, though it remains relevant to older historical rollouts.\n- In Evorto multi-worktree syncs, do not trust local `main`: fetch/compare `HEAD...origin/main` before branching; branch from refreshed detached `origin/main` or rebase immediately.\n- For the implemented Scaleway migration, retain the image-security gate: strip runtime `.map` files and `node_modules/@neondatabase`, scan first-party runtime artifacts, then run `bun run image:security:local` and `git diff --cached --check` before commit.\n- In Evorto detached worktrees, `git town hack \u003cbranch\u003e` is the proven branch-creation path before commit/push/PR work.\n- Evorto merges are squash-only; if another worktree already has `main` checked out, prefer `gh pr merge --squash --delete-branch` plus remote ref checks over Git Town recovery.\n- In `Window watcher`, verify Railway with live deployment state plus production `/app-version.json`; if a push does not deploy, `railway service source connect ...` is the proven recovery path, GitHub Actions should prove commit equality rather than only going green, and weather fallbacks should fail closed rather than inventing a current value…1193 tokens truncated…Roles, manual approval registration, email-delivery.ts, new schema, no migrations, git town hack, PR 83\n  - desc: Use this for relaunch-stack implementation or publish flows in detached Evorto worktrees; the durable rule is new schema only, no migration layer. [ad-hoc note]\n\n- Incomplete-implementation audit and current ticket-transfer behavior: INCOMPLETE_IMPLEMENTATIONS.md, transferMyRegistration, transferEventRegistration, current behavior, blocked paid transfer\n  - desc: Use this for whole-repo gap audits or “how does this work right now” questions in `cwd=/Users/hedde/.codex/worktrees/*/evorto`.\n\n- Dependency refresh and CI-only stacked PR workflow: angular-22, typescript-6, node-24.15.0, @types/pg, run the tests only in ci, PR 76\n  - desc: Use this for Evorto dependency refreshes on top of an existing stack when Angular 22 forces a toolchain decision or the user wants CI-only validation.\n\n- Stacked PR verification and PR body readiness: PR62, PR63, gh run watch, docs-baseline, EventConflictError, STABILIZATION.md\n  - desc: Use this for stacked-PR readiness checks, unresolved review-thread inspection, or PR body rewrites that must include local validation instructions.\n\n- Font Awesome Pro vendor workflow and separate PR publishing: fontawesome, GitHub Packages, FONT_AWESOME_TOKEN, build-fontawesome-vendor-package.ts, workflow_dispatch, PR 74\n  - desc: Use this for Evorto automation that mirrors the locked Font Awesome Pro package into GitHub Packages or for isolated workflow PRs.\n\n#### /Users/hedde/.codex/worktrees/*/section-app\n\n- Latest-main full audit and local-only regression hardening: section-app, af745039, server/.env.development, server/.env.test, server/src/generated/prisma, storageRouter, upload-retry, yarn lint:budget\n  - desc: Use this for `section-app` whole-app reviews, latest-main audits, DB-free runtime setup, or fixes around storage/profile/upload flows under strict no-prod/no-interference constraints.\n\n- DeepSource cleanup and terminal GitHub-app handoff: DeepSource, .deepsource.toml, deepsource.io, DeepSource Autofix, terminal handoff, PR 677, gh pr merge 677 --squash --delete-branch\n  - desc: Use this when `section-app` cleanup spans repo config removal plus GitHub app-access cleanup or a broken browser-auth/settings flow.\n\n- Dependency modernization and DB-free verification baseline: DEPENDENCY_REVIEW.md, yarn@4.1.1, RUN_PROVIDER_E2E, Angular 22.0.6, high/critical zero\n  - desc: Use this for `section-app` dependency-upgrade work that should stay provider-free by default and leave a ranked `DEPENDENCY_REVIEW.md` artifact.\n\n- Multi-PR coordination and overlap avoidance: parallel PR, overlap, wait, rebase, sync main, codex/analytics-auth-hardening, PR 677\n  - desc: Use this when a `section-app` branch may collide with another in-flight PR and the user wants duplicate work paused or trimmed in `cwd=/Users/hedde/.codex/worktrees/*/section-app`.\n\n#### /Users/hedde/Documents/Codex/2026-07-12/c\n\n- Browser inventory and selective removal on macOS: macOS, Safari, Google Chrome, Arc, ChatGPT Atlas, Cryptex, PlistBuddy, osascript, ~/.Trash\n  - desc: Use this for local macOS browser discovery or lightweight app-bundle uninstall requests on this machine.\n\n#### /Users/hedde/.codex/worktrees/*/evorto-pages\n\n- Vercel deployment recovery and production verification: Vercel, outputDirectory, apps/marketing-page/.next, apps/documentation-page/.next, vercel project update, nodeVersion 24.x\n  - desc: Use this for `evorto-pages` production deploy failures where builds succeed but Vercel cannot find the Next output directory in `cwd=/Users/hedde/.codex/worktrees/*/evorto-pages`.\n\n#### /Users/hedde/code/effect-angular\n\n- Angular/Effect upgrade and release automation hardening: effect-angular, Angular 22.0.6, Effect 4.0.0-beta.97, repos/effect, Dependabot, Knope, regex-backed versioned_files\n  - desc: Use this for `effect-angular` upgrade/review work, Effect source vendoring, Dependabot auto-merge policy, or Knope release PR failures.\n\n#### /Users/hedde/code/docs-tests\n\n- Open-source release bootstrap and gh-driven publishing: docs-tests, npm trust, trusted publishing, gh release create, Protect main, docs-tests@0.1.0\n  - desc: Use this for `docs-tests` first-release bootstrap, GitHub-side release config, or trusted-publishing setup in `cwd=/Users/hedde/code/docs-tests`.\n\n#### /Users/hedde/code/evorto\n\n- Neon Local branch management and cleanup: neonctl, neon_local, polished-frost-79768881, PARENT_BRANCH_ID, db-expiration, NEON_LOCAL_BRANCH_TTL_HOURS\n  - desc: Use this for `cwd=/Users/hedde/code/evorto` bulk Neon branch deletion, branch-explosion forensics, or the pushed TTL mitigation on `main`.\n\n- Conservative branch sync skill: skills/update-evorto-branch/SKILL.md, git fetch --no-tags, git ls-remote, FETCH_HEAD\n  - desc: Separate reusable procedure for safe `origin` sync checks in `cwd=/Users/hedde/code/evorto` when the task is “latest changes” or automation branch verification, not Neon cleanup.\n========= MEMORY_SUMMARY ENDS =========\n\nWhen memory is likely relevant, start with the quick memory pass above before\ndeep repo exploration.\n","type":"input_text"},{"text":"\u003capps_instructions\u003e\n## Apps (Connectors)\nApps (Connectors) can be explicitly triggered in user messages in the format `[$app-name](app://{connector_id})`. Apps can also be implicitly triggered as long as the context suggests usage of available apps.\nAn app is equivalent to a set of MCP tools within the `codex_apps` MCP.\nAn installed app's MCP tools are either provided to you already, or can be lazy-loaded through the `tool_search` tool. If `tool_search` is available, the apps that are searchable by `tools_search` will be listed by it.\nDo not additionally call list_mcp_resources or list_mcp_resource_templates for apps.\n\u003c/apps_instructions\u003e","type":"input_text"},{"text":"\u003cplugins_instructions\u003e\n## Plugins\nA plugin is a local bundle of skills, MCP servers, and apps.\n### How to use plugins\n- Skill naming: If a plugin contributes skills, those skill entries are prefixed with `plugin_name:` in the Skills list.\n- MCP naming: Plugin-provided MCP tools keep standard MCP identifiers such as `mcp__server__tool`; use tool provenance to tell which plugin they come from.\n- Trigger rules: If the user explicitly names a plugin, prefer capabilities associated with that plugin for that turn.\n- Relationship to capabilities: Plugins are not invoked directly. Use their underlying skills, MCP tools, and app tools to help solve the task.\n- Relevance: Determine what a plugin can help with from explicit user mention or from the plugin-associated skills, MCP tools, and apps exposed elsewhere in this turn.\n- Missing/blocked: If the user requests a plugin that does not have relevant callable capabilities for the task, say so briefly and continue with the best fallback.\n\u003c/plugins_instructions\u003e","type":"input_text"},{"text":"\u003cskills_instructions\u003e\n## Skills\nA skill is a set of local instructions to follow that is stored in a `SKILL.md` file. Below is the list of skills that can be used. Each entry includes a name, description, and a short path that can be expanded into an absolute path using the skill roots table.\n### Skill roots\n- `r0` = `/Users/hedde/.codex/skills`\n- `r1` = `/Users/hedde/.agents/skills`\n- `r2` = `/Users/hedde/.codex/skills/.system`\n- `r3` = `/Users/hedde/.codex/plugins/cache/openai-bundled`\n- `r4` = `/Users/hedde/.codex/plugins/cache/openai-bundled/sites/0.1.30/skills`\n- `r5` = `/Users/hedde/.codex/plugins/cache/openai-curated-remote/codex-security/0.1.11/skills`\n- `r6` = `/Users/hedde/.codex/plugins/cache/openai-curated-remote/figma/2.0.14-alpha.0/skills`\n- `r7` = `/Users/hedde/.codex/plugins/cache/openai-curated-remote`\n- `r8` = `/Users/hedde/.codex/plugins/cache/openai-curated-remote/google-calendar/1.2.4/skills`\n- `r9` = `/Users/hedde/.codex/plugins/cache/openai-curated-remote/google-drive/0.1.10/skills`\n- `r10` = `/Users/hedde/.codex/plugins/cache/openai-curated-remote/product-design/0.1.50/skills`\n- `r11` = `/Users/hedde/.codex/plugins/cache/openai-curated-remote/workspace-agents/0.1.13/skills`\n- `r12` = `/Users/hedde/.codex/plugins/cache/openai-primary-runtime`\n- `r13` = `/Users/hedde/.codex/plugins/cache/openai-primary-runtime/spreadsheets/26.715.12143/skills`\n- `r14` = `/Users/hedde/.codex/worktrees/b7e9/evorto/.agents/skills`\n### Available skills\n- imagegen: Generate or edit raster images when the task benefits from AI-created bitmap visuals s (file: r2/imagegen/SKILL.md)\n- openai-docs: Use when the user asks how to build with OpenAI products or APIs, asks about Codex i (file: r2/openai-docs/SKILL.md)\n- plugin-creator: Create and scaffold plugin directories for Codex with a required `.codex-plugin/plugin (file: r2/plugin-creator/SKILL.md)\n- skill-creator: Guide for creating effective skills. This skill should be used when users want to cr (file: r2/skill-creator/SKILL.md)\n- skill-installer: Install Codex skills into $CODEX_HOME/skills from a curated list or a GitHub repo pa (file: r2/skill-installer/SKILL.md)\n- effect-ts: Use this skill whenever working in a repository that uses Effect, even if the current t (file: r14/effect-ts/SKILL.md)\n- material-3:material-3: Implement Google's Material Design 3 (Material You) UI system. Primary: Jetpack Compos (file: r14/material-3/SKILL.md)\n- project-design: Project-specific UI and styling guidance for Evorto, including when to use viewport q (file: r14/project-design/SKILL.md)\n- two-column-page-pattern: Implement Evorto two-column list/detail page layout with responsive grid, mobile list h (file: r14/two-column-page-pattern/SKILL.md)\n- uncodixfy: Prevents generic AI/Codex UI patterns when generating frontend code. Use this skill whe (file: r14/uncodixfy/SKILL.md)\n- Vibe-Security-Skill: This skill helps Claude write secure web applications. Use when working on any web a (file: r1/vibe-security-skill/SKILL.md)\n- VibeSec-Skill: This skill helps Claude write secure web applications. Use this when working on any  (file: r1/vibesec-skill/SKILL.md)\n- angular-component: Create modern Angular standalone components following v20+ best practices. Use for b (file: r1/angular-component/SKILL.md)\n- angular-developer: Generates Angular code and provides architectural guidance. Trigger when creating pr (file: r1/angular-developer/SKILL.md)\n- angular-di: Implement dependency injection in Angular v20+ using inject(), injection tokens, and p (file: r1/angular-di/SKILL.md)\n- angular-directives: Create custom directives in Angular v20+ for DOM manipulation and behavior extension.  (file: r1/angular-directives/SKILL.md)\n- angular-forms: Build signal-based forms in Angular v21+ using the new Signal Forms API. Use for for (file: r1/angular-forms/SKILL.md)\n- angular-http: Implement HTTP data fetching in Angular v20+ using resource(), httpResource(), and Htt (file: r1/angular-http/SKILL.md)\n- angular-new-app: Creates a new Angular app using the Angular CLI. This skill should be used whenever  (file: r1/angular-new-app/SKILL.md)\n- angular-routing: Implement routing in Angular v20+ applications with lazy loading, functional guards, (file: r1/angular-routing/SKILL.md)\n- angular-signals: Implement signal-based reactive state management in Angular v20+. Use for creating r (file: r1/angular-signals/SKILL.md)\n- angular-ssr: Implement server-side rendering and hydration in Angular v20+ using @angular/ssr. Us (file: r1/angular-ssr/SKILL.md)\n- angular-testing: Write unit and integration tests for Angular v20+ applications using Vitest or Jasmi (file: r1/angular-testing/SKILL.md)\n- angular-tooling: Use Angular CLI and development tools effectively in Angular v20+ projects. Use for  (file: r1/angular-tooling/SKILL.md)\n- atlas: macOS-only AppleScript control for the ChatGPT Atlas desktop app. Use only when the  (file: r0/atlas/SKILL.md)\n- browser:control-in-app-browser: Control the in-app Browser for opening, navigating, inspecting visible or interactive  (file: r3/browser/26.715.31925/skills/control-in-app-browser/SKILL.md)\n- chrome:control-chrome: Control the user's Chrome browser for tasks that depend on existing Chrome state: ta (file: r3/chrome/26.715.31925/skills/control-chrome/SKILL.md)\n- codex-security:attack-path-analysis: Use when Codex is already in the attack-path-analysis phase of a security scan or the u (file: r5/attack-path-analysis/SKILL.md)\n- codex-security:deep-security-scan: Use when the user asks for a deep, exhaustive, multi-pass, or variance-reducing reposit (file: r5/deep-security-scan/SKILL.md)\n- codex-security:finding-discovery: Use when Codex is already in the finding-discovery phase of a security scan or the us (file: r5/finding-discovery/SKILL.md)\n- codex-security:fix-finding: Use when the user explicitly asks to fix and verify a validated or plausible security (file: r5/fix-finding/SKILL.md)\n- codex-security:propose-security-hardening: Develop evidence-backed structural and architectural security hardening proposals from  (file: r5/propose-security-hardening/SKILL.md)\n- codex-security:security-diff-scan: Use when the user asks for a security review of a pull request, commit, branch diff, wo (file: r5/security-diff-scan/SKILL.md)\n- codex-security:security-scan: Use for a standard, single-pass security audit of an entire repository or a scoped pa (file: r5/security-scan/SKILL.md)\n- codex-security:threat-model: Use when Codex is already in the threat-modeling phase of a security scan, the user exp (file: r5/threat-model/SKILL.md)\n- codex-security:track-findings: Track validated Codex Security findings in Linear, Jira, GitHub issues, or draft GitHub (file: r5/track-findings/SKILL.md)\n- codex-security:triage-finding: Use when the user supplies or imports existing security findings, vulnerability reports (file: r5/triage-finding/SKILL.md)\n- codex-security:validation: Use when Codex is already in the validation phase of a security scan or the user explic (file: r5/validation/SKILL.md)\n- codex-security:vulnerability-writeup: Write up vulnerabilities from disclosure documents, rough notes, supplied findings, P (file: r5/vulnerability-writeup/SKILL.md)\n- computer-use:computer-use: Control local Mac apps through Computer Use for tasks that require reading or operati (file: r3/computer-use/1.0.1000451/skills/computer-use/SKILL.md)\n- documents:documents: Create, edit